### Swift Optional Chaining

Optional chaining allows you to safely access properties, methods, and subscripts on an optional that might be `nil`. If the optional is `nil`, the entire chain fails gracefully and returns `nil`.

**Optional Chaining Syntax:**

```swift
class Person {
    var residence: Residence?
}

class Residence {
    var address: Address?
}

class Address {
    var street: String?
}

let person = Person()
let streetName = person.residence?.address?.street
// streetName is String? (nil if any part is nil)
```

**Common Use Cases:**

| Operation | Syntax | Result Type |
|-----------|--------|-------------|
| Property access | `optional?.property` | Optional of property type |
| Method call | `optional?.method()` | `Void?` |
| Subscript | `optional?[index]` | Optional of element type |
| Assignment | `optional?.property = value` | Only if not nil |

```swift
let count = person.residence?.numberOfRooms
// Returns Int? regardless of numberOfRooms return type

// Setting a property through optional chaining
person.residence?.numberOfRooms = 3
// Only executes if residence is not nil
```

> **Key Point:** Optional chaining can be nested to any depth. The result type is always an optional, even if the final property is non-optional.

Optional chaining is the safe alternative to force unwrapping chains of optionals.

codeExample:
import Foundation

class Book {
    var title: String
    var author: String?

    init(title: String) {
        self.title = title
    }
}

class Library {
    var books: [Book]?
}

let library = Library()
library.books = [Book(title: "1984"), Book(title: "Swift Programming")]

// Optional chaining to access first book's title
let firstBookTitle = library.books?.first?.title
print("First book: \(firstBookTitle ?? "Unknown")")

// Optional chaining with method call
library.books?.append(Book(title: "Foundation"))
let bookCount = library.books?.count ?? 0
print("Total books: \(bookCount)")
